A TOP gospel singer considers himself lucky after spending four months in hospital.&nbsp; Khulekani Chilli told Sunday Sun he almost died of lung problems.&nbsp; The star spent four months, from December to March, at the Steve Biko Academic Hospital in Pretoria, fighting for his life.&nbsp; The gospel star saids he was diagnosed with fluid in the lungs.&nbsp; Khulekani said that as a result of his illness, he was unable to attend the funerals of his two friends: Sfiso Ncwane and Lundi Tyamara.&nbsp; &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t sleep well as this torments me a lot now that I wasn&rsquo;t able to pay my last respects to them,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp; The Phakama Baba hitmaker said it was sad to lose close friends and not be part of their memorial services and burials.&nbsp; &ldquo;It was sad for me to hear that Sfiso had died, and when I was almost accepting it, I received more sad news that Lundi had also passed on.&nbsp; &ldquo;All I wanted was to die on that hospital bed.&rdquo;&nbsp; Khulekani told the People&rsquo;s Paper that he had to deal with the pain alone, and remember the good and the bad times he had spent with his friends.&nbsp;He told Sunday Sun he&rsquo;s still in a fragile state, but is on the way to recovery.&nbsp; His plea to gospel singers was that they should meet and hold prayer sessions regularly.&nbsp; &ldquo;This because gospel singers are dying in mysterious ways and we don&rsquo;t know who&rsquo;s next,&rdquo; Khulekani said.&nbsp; Meanwhile, he has opted to live a life of, non-stop prayer.&nbsp; Khulekani released his new album, God is able, last month .&nbsp; According to the singer, the release of his album, which was scheduled for the past Easter holidays, had to be put on ice due to ill health.&nbsp; His fans will see him perform for the first time since his recovery at Moses Molelekwa Main Hall, near Makhulong Stadium in Tembisa, Ekurhuleni, on 29 July.&nbsp;